g.text: 2. On a Moral Vision: John Howard Yoder
John Howard Yoder believes the story of Jesus challenges both the Christian community and everyone
watching them. This story shows the purpose (or telos) of all history, though many people may reject
it. Yet Christians continue to follow Jesus because they see him as the true King. For Yoder,
faithfulness to Jesus is how believers help prove or bring about his authority.
Yoder says a truly eschatological viewpoint (one that looks toward the
ultimate future God promises). Hope is key in this vision. Yoder’s
ethical ideas grew out of the Anabaptist tradition, which tries to live
as the original New Testament church did—through discipleship,
voluntary membership, and nonviolence.
Yoder’s Alternative Community of Hermeneutics
McClendon agrees with MacIntyre that many virtues arise from shared
practices in a tradition. He also agrees with Yoder that the church’s
practices must be rooted in the eschatological (future-directed) body
of Christ.
3. On Convictional Communities: James William McClendon
McClendon’s major idea is that “convictions” define the deepest
commitments of a person or group.
Convictions are more than abstract principles; they are beliefs bound up with emotions, desires, and
ways of living. They influence both our character (the kind of people we become) and our actions (how
we behave). And because actions also shape character, it’s a cycle: we form our convictions, and our
convictions form us.
For McClendon, the local congregation is the place where Christian convictions are formed, tested, and
practiced. It’s where believers:
The Role of Community
He critiques purely “top-down” church structures or focusing on personal morality in isolation. Instead,
McClendon says that shared worship, teaching, discipline, and service in the local church build the kind
of community that truly lives out the story of Jesus.
Convictions and Character
Narrative and Virtue
McClendon argues that life stories (“biographies”) can actually do theological work. By studying the
biographies of notable Christians (“the saints”), we see how their convictions shaped their lives.
These life stories are part of Jesus’ own story, because the church’s calling is to live out
Christ’s way in each generation. Narratives help us avoid self-deception by comparing our own lives
to the example of Christ, enabling us to revise our beliefs and behaviors as needed.
Biography as Theology
McClendon concludes that true theology and ethics can’t exist in a vacuum. They arise from the
interplay of convictions, community life, storytelling, and worship. By paying close attention to the
community’s primary theology, the church’s “academic” or “secondary” theology can stay faithful
to the lived reality of Christian discipleship.
Ultimately, McClendon says that “this is that” and “then is now” unite the church
across time. The baptist vision means we interpret and live Scripture as if its words
apply directly to us, here and now, expecting God’s final future to break into our
present lives—making us a community of virtue shaped by the life, death, and
resurrection of Christ.
Key Marks of the McClendon Baptist Vision
“This is that”
“Then is now”
Taking inspiration from Acts 2:16 (“This is that which was spoken by
the prophet…”), McClendon says that God’s Word for the past
applies directly to our present. The original events in the Bible
aren’t just ancient history; they live on in the church today.
Just as “this is that” links the present to biblical stories, “then is
now” reminds us that God’s future (the end times) breaks into the
current moment. We aren’t simply waiting for some distant future;
the eschatological reality (God’s reign) is already shaping our life
here and now.
